                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18470920-2253-offence-2" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470920-2253-offence-2" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470920-2253-offence-2" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp> for feloniously receiving the same, knowing them to be stolen.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1283" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1283" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1283" type="surname" value="JENKINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1283" type="given" value="WILLIAM KINNAIRD"></interp>WILLIAM KINNAIRD JENKINS.</persName>
                  </hi> I live in Victoria Villas, Avilla-road, Regent's Park. Bowley was in my service—about the 27th April, I lost six spoons—these two spoons are mine—they have my mark on them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1284" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1284" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1284" type="surname" value="COOK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1284" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY COOK.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a pawnbroker. I produce these two spoons—Bow<lb></lb>ley offered them to me on the 27th of April—she asked 22<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for them—seeing they were two different crests I asked whose they were—she said they belonged to her sister—I told her to fetch her sister, and in the mean time I sent a young man to watch her, to see where she went to—she walked</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184709200220"></xptr>
               <p>about the road for some time, came back, and said her sister wanted them back again, and she would not pawn them at all—the young man I had sent came in, and said she had not been anywhere, only walking about—she seemed confused, and then said she would fetch her sister—she went out, and not coming for an hour I went with the officer to the address she gave me, No. 3, Smith's-place—I saw her sitting at tea with her sister, the prisoner Ashberry—I gave her in charge—Ashberry said, "Good God, you have done for yourself now; come in, the neighbours will hear of it now."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1285" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1285" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1285" type="surname" value="CUDDY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1285" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES CUDDY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, L</hi> 20.) On the 27th of Aug., I was called by Mr. Cook, and went with him to No. 3, Smith's-place, Gibraltar-row—we found Bowley sitting there—Mr. Cook pointed her out as the person who had offered the spoons—I asked her if she wanted to say anything about the two spoons that she had offered—she said, "Let me have them, I will take them home to my master"—I said, "Where does he live?"—she said, "No.9, Avilla-road, Regent's-part, and his name Jenkins"—I took her to the station—I came back to the house, and asked Ashberry if her sister had left any duplicates there—she said, "No"—I saw her give something to Mr. Cook—I asked what it was, and he gave me a duplicate for two spoons—I said to Ashberry, "Have you any more?"—she handed me a duplicate for two spoons, pawned on the 1st July—she then said, "I have given all I have got, you may search if you please"—I said, "I will not take you, as you have a family; come before the Magistrate to-morrow morning"—I went to Mr. Jenkin's, and found three more duplicates for spoons pawned at Mr. Attenborough's—I went the next day to Ashberry's, and asked why she was not in attendance before the Magistrate—she said, "I went after my girl that pawned the two tea-spoons.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Bowley's Defence.</hi> My sister did not know that they were my master's property.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">BOWLEY</hi>—
